Requirements: Unconditional admission to the University of North Alabama Graduate Studies. Clear and unencumbered Registered Nurse license in the state where clinicals will be completed. Master of Science degree in Nursing from an accredited (ACEN or CCNE) university with a minimum 3.0 GPA. National certification as an advanced practice nurse. Completion of the following graduate courses with a "B" or better: Advanced Pathophysiology, Advanced Pharmacology, and Advanced Physical Assessment. PMHNP applicants must have one year of full-time work experience as a Registered Nurse in a psychiatric mental health setting within the last five years. Submit a resume. Submit a copy of APRN national certification. Submit a copy of graduate transcripts. Submit to a formal interview with graduate nursing faculty.
Department: Anderson College of Nursing and Health Professions
Description: The post-graduate APRN certificate curriculum is designed to provide the master’s or doctoral prepared nurse who is nationally certified and licensed as an advanced practice registered nurse (APRN), with the opportunity to expand their scope of practice into a new specialty area of advanced practice nursing. The curriculum provides a structured program of study in one of five concentrations. A certificate is awarded upon completion of the program. Certificate-prepared graduates are eligible to take the national certification examination in the area of their concentration.
Accredidation: The post-graduate APRN certificate program at the University of North Alabama are accredited by the Commission on Collegiate Nursing Education, 655 K Street, NW, Suite 750, Washington, DC 20001, 202-887-6791.

EnglishScore: UNA requires a satisfactory score on the Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL), International English Language Testing System (IELTS), Pearson Test of English Academic (PTE), Duolingo, or ELS Language Centers level 112 for applicants whose native language is not English.
Department: College of Arts, Sciences, and Engineering
Description: Applied Behavior Analysis (ABA) is a science that focuses on improving significant behaviors (e.g., social skills, communication, daily living skills, etc.) and decreasing challenging behaviors (e.g., aggression, self-injury, etc.) through the use of evidence-based procedures. Applied Behavior Analysis is the leading, most effective, evidence-based treatment for individuals with Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD). The principles of ABA are often used to build skills and treat challenging behavior in other populations as well, including those with developmental and intellectual disabilities, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, and conduct disorder. The Minor in Applied Behavior Analysis is designed to provide students with a fundamental understanding of the principles of behavior and how to apply them to improve the lives of others. The Association for Behavior Analysis International has verified the following courses toward the coursework requirements for eligibility to take the Board Certified Assistant Behavior Analyst® examination. Applicants will need to meet additional requirements before they can be deemed eligible to take the examination.

EnglishScore: The University of North Alabama requires official English proficiency scores from all international applicants unless they meet an exemption. Accepted tests include TOEFL with a minimum score of 70 (Internet-based), IELTS with a minimum score of 5.5, PTE Academic with a minimum score of 48, Duolingo with a minimum score of 95, or completion of ELS Level 112.
Requirements:
To be admitted to the MPA Program, a student must meet the admission requirements of the Office of Graduate Studies. In addition, the student must meet the requirements of the MPA program, which are as follows:

1. Submit an application for admission to graduate study.
2. Submit official transcripts from all colleges and universities attended.
3. Possess an overall undergraduate grade point average of 2.75 or higher on a 4.0 scale.
4. Submit a letter of application to the MPA Program Director. The letter of application will be used to determine the applicant’s aptitude for graduate study and for a public service career. The letter must address the following areas:
   * Why the applicant wants to pursue the MPA degree.
   * The applicant’s career goals.
   * What the applicant expects to gain from the MPA program.
   * The applicant's understanding of public service.
5. Submit a writing sample that demonstrates the applicant’s ability to write clearly and concisely. The writing sample may be a paper written for a previous course or a work product.
6. Submit two letters of recommendation.
Department: College of Arts, Sciences, and Engineering
Description: The Master of Public Administration (MPA) degree is the recognized professional degree for individuals who are seeking a career in public service. The MPA program at UNA is a generalist program designed for individuals employed or seeking employment in public or non-profit sector. The mission of the Master of Public Administration (MPA) program at the University of North Alabama is to provide a quality and accessible graduate education for current and future leaders of public and nonprofit organizations, domestically and abroad. We promote public service values that include accountability, transparency, social equity, and diversity. This is achieved through an innovative and engaging curriculum, along with a faculty committed to teaching, research and service. Students can participate in our student led Public Administration Club as well as join the Pi Alpha Alpha National Honors Society for Public Affairs and Administration. The MPA Program has three tracks: Generalist, Public Human Resource Management, and Criminal Justice Administration. The 36-hour program includes 24 hours of core courses and 12 hours of electives from one of the three tracks.
Accredidation: The UNA Master of Public Administration (MPA) program is accredited by the Network of Schools of Public Policy, Affairs, and Administration (NASPAA) – The Global Standard in Public Service Education.

EnglishScore: Proof of English Proficiency required for international students. Options include TOEFL (IBT 79, PBT 550), IELTS (6.0), PTEA (54), Duolingo (110), ELS (Level 112), or English Composition I & II with a C or better from a US accredited college/university.
Requirements: Unconditional Admission: An undergraduate degree from a regionally accredited institution with a cumulative GPA of 2.75 or higher on a 4.0 scale. Submit an application for admission, official transcripts from all colleges/universities attended, and the non-refundable application fee. Submit a statement of purpose for seeking the MPA degree at UNA (250-500 words). Submit a current resume or vita. Submit an academic or professional writing sample. Submit three letters of recommendation from professional or academic sources.
Concentration: Criminal Justice Administration, Public Human Resources Management, Public Policy
Description: The Master of Public Administration (MPA) degree at the University of North Alabama is an interdisciplinary graduate degree designed to prepare students for leadership and management careers in the public and non-profit sectors. The MPA degree combines the theory and practice of public administration, enabling students to develop the skills necessary for a career in government, nonprofit management, or a related field. The UNA MPA program has a diverse student population and is delivered entirely online, providing the flexibility students need to succeed. Our mission is to produce highly competent, ethical leaders committed to public service and the betterment of their communities. The MPA program serves a diverse student population, preparing them for leadership roles in a variety of public and non-profit organizations. Through innovative online coursework and engaged, applied learning, we empower students with the knowledge, skills, and values required to address complex societal challenges and promote the public good. We value professionalism, ethics, equity, diversity, and collaboration in all that we do.
Accredidation: The Master of Public Administration (MPA) program at the University of North Alabama is accredited by the Network of Schools of Public Policy, Affairs, and Administration (NASPAA) Commission on Peer Review and Accreditation and is listed on the Annual Roster of Accredited Programs in conformity with NASPAA standards.

Baccalaureate degree from an accredited institution.
Minimum 2.5 GPA on a 4.0 scale on all previous coursework.
Official transcripts from all institutions attended.
UNA Graduate application for admission.
Application fee.

Description: The Graduate Certificate in Public Health is a 15-credit hour program designed for current graduate students or post-baccalaureate students who desire foundational knowledge in public health. This certificate is open to students from all academic disciplines who desire to enhance their knowledge and skills in public health. The coursework can be completed in two semesters, and all courses are taught online. Students completing the certificate program can apply these credits toward completion of the Master of Science in Health and Human Performance, Public Health concentration.

EnglishScore: All international applicants must submit an official score report from one of the following tests of English proficiency: TOEFL, IELTS or PTE. The minimum acceptable scores are: 79 on the iBT (or 550 on the pBT), 6.5 on the IELTS, or 59 on the PTE.
Requirements: An application to The University of Alabama Graduate School; Official transcripts from all institutions attended; A bachelor’s degree from a regionally accredited institution; A minimum undergraduate GPA of 3.0 on a 4.0 scale; A three- to five-page statement of purpose detailing your interest in public health, career goals and how the MPH degree will help you achieve them; Three letters of recommendation; A current résumé or curriculum vitae; GRE is not required for admission.
Department: College of Community Health Sciences

EnglishScore: International applicants whose native language is not English must submit evidence of English proficiency by providing a minimum score on one of the following: TOEFL iBT (79), IELTS (6.0), PTE Academic (54), Duolingo (100), or completion of ELS Level 112.
Requirements:
Admission to the Master of Health Administration Program is open to qualified holders of bachelor’s degrees from regionally accredited institutions. Applicants are admitted to the program on the basis of criteria that suggest a high probability of success. The following are the requirements for admission:

1. Completed Application for Graduate Studies.
2. Official transcript(s) from all colleges/universities attended with a posted bachelor's degree from a regionally accredited institution submitted directly from the colleges or universities.
3. Bachelor's degree with a minimum cumulative GPA of 2.75 on a 4.0 scale.
4. Submission of a current resume.
5. Submission of a letter of intent.
6. Submission of two letters of recommendation.
Department: College of Business and Technology

EnglishScore: Students from non-English speaking countries must submit an official score report from one of the following testing agencies: TOEFL Internet-based test (iBT) score of 79, IELTS score of 6.0, PTE Academic score of 54, Duolingo score of 110, or successful completion of ELS Language Center's level 112. Test scores must be less than two years old.
Requirements:
Students applying for admission must submit the following to the Office of Graduate Admissions:
1. Completed UNA Graduate Application and fee.
2. Official transcripts from all postsecondary institutions attended submitted directly to the Office of Graduate Admissions from the institution. The transcript must document a conferred bachelor's degree from a regionally accredited institution.
3. An undergraduate GPA of 2.75 on a 4.0 scale.
4. Personal statement of no more than 500 words describing the applicant's purpose in pursuing graduate study in public health.
5. Resume

Department: Anderson College of Nursing and Health Professions
Description: The Anderson College of Nursing and Health Professions, School of Nursing offers a Master of Science in Public Health degree program. The program is designed for students seeking a graduate degree for professional advancement in the public health workforce. The program will equip students for public health careers in a wide range of settings, including community organizations, government agencies, health care, and academics. Students will gain knowledge and skills in the five core public health discipline areas: biostatistics, epidemiology, health policy and management, social and behavioral sciences, and environmental health sciences. The program consists of 42 credit hours. It is offered entirely online, allowing flexibility for students. The program includes an Applied Practice Experience and an Integrative Learning Experience that allow students to apply their knowledge and skills in real-world settings.
Accredidation: The Master of Science in Public Health at the University of North Alabama is an applicant for accreditation by the Council on Education for Public Health (CEPH). The accreditation review will address the Master of Science in Public Health. Other degrees and areas of study offered by this institution will not be included in the unit of accreditation review.

EnglishScore: International students must satisfy the UNA requirements for international student admission, including English proficiency. One of the following official scores is required: TOEFL iBT: 79, IELTS: 6.0, PTE: 54, or Duolingo: 110.
Requirements: Overall GPA of 3.0 or higher. Grade of 'B' or better in all pre-requisite courses for the Public Health Program. Submit a formal application to the Graduate Admissions office. Submit a one-page, double-spaced personal statement addressing why you want to be a public health professional and what makes you a good candidate for the Public Health program and a career in public health. Submit three letters of recommendation with at least one letter from a UNA faculty member. Submit a resume or curriculum vitae. Once a complete application has been submitted, the applicant will be scheduled for an interview with the Graduate Coordinator.
Department: College of Education and Human Sciences
Description: The University of North Alabama’s Accelerated Master of Science in Public Health (AMSPH) is a 42-credit hour, fully online program that will prepare students to address the most pressing public health issues regionally, nationally, and globally. Our program builds on public health’s core functions: assessment, policy development, and assurance, while integrating the social determinants of health. Students will learn how to identify community assets and needs, plan and implement evidence-based programs, evaluate program and policy effectiveness, and advocate for health equity.
Accredidation: The UNA Public Health Program is a new and developing program. The program is an applicant for accreditation by the Council on Education for Public Health (CEPH). The program is not accredited by CEPH at this time.

EnglishScore: All applicants whose native language is not English are required to submit proof of English proficiency. This can be met by providing an official score report for one of the following: TOEFL with a minimum score of 79 on the iBT (internet-based test) or 550 on the PBT (paper-based test); IELTS with a minimum score of 6.0; PTE with a minimum score of 54; Duolingo with a minimum score of 105; or successful completion of Level 112 of the English Language Services (ELS) intensive program.
Requirements:
Admission to the Master of Public Policy (MPP) program is granted through the UNA Office of Graduate Admissions.

Applicants for the Master of Public Policy must meet the following requirements:

* An official transcript from the college or university that awarded the baccalaureate degree, with a minimum cumulative undergraduate GPA of 2.75 on a 4.0 scale.
* Two letters of recommendation from former professors or professionals familiar with the applicant’s academic and/or professional capabilities.
* A current résumé.
* A 500-word statement of purpose outlining the applicant’s reasons for pursuing the MPP degree.
* For applicants with a GPA below 2.75, a 300-word statement explaining any extenuating circumstances for the lower GPA.
* The Graduate Record Examination (GRE) is not required for admission into the MPP program.
* The Public Affairs program coordinator may request a meeting (phone, online, or in-person) with the applicant if the need for one is determined.
Description: The Master of Public Policy (M.P.P.) is the professional public service degree that prepares students for careers as analysts, managers, and leaders in the public, non-profit, and private sectors. The curriculum is designed to teach students to be creative problem-solvers, providing them with the tools and skills necessary to address a wide range of societal problems. With a focus on applied learning, the M.P.P. emphasizes hands-on experience and real-world problem-solving. This includes opportunities for research, community-engaged learning projects, and internships. The M.P.P. is a 36-hour program that students can complete online, in person, or a combination of both. It can be completed in as little as 12 months for full-time students. The program is flexible to accommodate the schedules of working professionals.

EnglishScore: The University of Houston requires official, passing TOEFL or IELTS or Duolingo English Test (DET) scores for all applicants who are not U.S. citizens or U.S. permanent residents, unless they have earned a bachelor's or master's degree from a U.S. institution or from a country where English is the official language.
Requirements: The application process for the Valenti School of Communication's graduate program is a two-step process. In addition to applying to the University of Houston graduate school, applicants must submit the following supplemental materials: A 500-word statement of purpose detailing your interest in the graduate program, your career goals and how the M.A. program will help you achieve them; A current resume; A writing sample (e.g., a paper you have written for a class, a press release, or a research paper); Three letters of recommendation from faculty or professionals; Official transcripts from all previous institutions; Official GRE scores (UH code 6870). GRE waivers are available.

EnglishScore: Evidence of English proficiency is required for all non-native English speaking applicants. Applicants must meet one of the following requirements: Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) Internet-Based Test (IBT) with a score of 79. International English Language Testing System (IELTS) with a score of 6.0. Pearson Test of English Academic (PTE) with a score of 54. Duolingo English Test with a score of 100. Completion of English Language Services (ELS) Level 112.
Requirements: In addition to meeting the general requirements for admission to the Office of Graduate Studies, the applicant must meet the following program requirements: 1. A bachelor’s degree from a regionally accredited institution. 2. At least a 2.75 overall GPA on all undergraduate work. 3. Two letters of recommendation. 4. A personal essay that introduces the student and explains the student’s reasons for pursuing the master’s degree in writing. 5. A portfolio of student writing (approximately 15-20 pages).
Department: College of Arts, Sciences, and Engineering
Description: The Master of Arts in Writing at the University of North Alabama offers students the opportunity for advanced study in the fields of creative and professional writing. The program helps prepare students for careers in writing and for further graduate study. Students can specialize in creative writing, which offers a variety of workshops and literature courses, or composition/rhetoric, which offers courses in rhetorical theory, composition pedagogy, and the history of rhetoric. Both tracks require 36 hours of coursework, which can be completed in two years. With a graduate degree in writing from UNA, students may enter writing and editing professions in business and industry, teach in high schools or two-year colleges, or pursue doctoral degrees in English, Composition/Rhetoric, or Creative Writing.
